 Donald (imprint)|John Donald]] |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-85976-628-9 |pages=123\u2013159 |ref=B7 }}\n*{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/23713 |title=Robert II (1316\u20131390) |last=Boardman |first=SI |authorlink=Steve Boardman (historian) |year=2006 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/23713 |access-date=6 September 2011 |ref=B4}}\n*{{cite book |last=Caldwell |first=D |year=2008 |title=Islay: The Land of the Lordship |publisher=[[Birlinn (publisher)|Birlinn]] |location=Edinburgh |ref=C5 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Cameron |first=C |chapter='Contumaciously Absent'? The Lords of the Isles and the Scottish Crown |year=2014 |editor-last=Oram |editor-first=RD |editor-link=Richard Oram |title=The Lordship of the Isles |series=The Northern World: North Europe and the Baltic c. 400\u20131700 AD. Peoples, Economics and Cultures (series vol. 68) |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]] |location=Leiden |doi=10.1163/9789004280359_008 |isbn=978-90-04-28035-9 |issn=1569-1462 |pages=146\u2013175 |ref=C4 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Campbell of Airds |first=A |authorlink=Alastair Lorne Campbell of Airds |year=2000 |title=A History of Clan Campbell |volume=Vol. 1, From Origins to Flodden |publisher=[[Polygon at Edinburgh]] |location=Edinburgh |isbn=1-902930-17-7 |ref=C2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Campbell of Airds |first=A |authorlink=Alastair Lorne Campbell of Airds |chapter=West Highland Heraldry and The Lordship of the Isles |year=2014 |editor-last=Oram |editor-first=RD |editor-link=Richard Oram |title=The Lordship of the Isles |series=The Northern World: North Europe and the Baltic c. 400\u20131700 AD. Peoples, Economics and Cultures (series vol. 68) |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]] |location=Leiden |doi=10.1163/9789004280359_010 |isbn=978-90-04-28035-9 |issn=1569-1462 |pages=200\u2013210 |ref=C3 }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Coira |first=MP |year=2008 |title=The Earl of Argyll and the Goill: The 'Flodden Poem' Revisited |journal=Scottish Gaelic Studies |volume= 24 |pages=137\u2013168 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref=C1 }}\n*{{cite thesis |last=Daniels |first=PW |title=The Second Scottish War of Independence, 1332\u201341: A National War? |degree=MA |url=http://theses.gla.ac.uk/4640 |year=2013 |publisher=[[University of Glasgow]] |via=[[Glasgow Theses Service]] |ref=D2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Duncan |first=AAM |authorlink1=Archie Duncan (historian) |year=1998 |origyear=1993 |chapter=The 'Laws of Malcolm MacKenneth' |editor1-last=Grant |editor1-first=A |editor2-last=Stringer |editor2-first=KJ |title=Medieval Scotland: Crown, Lordship and Community |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |location=Edinburgh |pages=239\u2013273 |isbn=0-7486-1110-X |ref=D1 }}\n*{{cite book |year=2005 |last=Fisher |first=I |chapter=The Heirs of Somerled |editor1-last=Oram |editor1-first=RD |editor1-link=Richard Oram |editor2-last=Stell |editor2-first=GP |title=Lordship and Architecture in Medieval and Renaissance Scotland |publisher=[[John Donald (imprint)|John Donald]] |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-85976-628-9 |pages=85\u201395 |ref=F2 }}\n*{{cite thesis |last=Johnston |first=AR |year=1991 |title=Norse Settlement in the Inner Hebrides ca. 800\u20131300; With Special Reference to the Islands of Mull, Coll and Tiree |publisher=[[University of St Andrews]] |hdl=10023/2950 |degree=PhD |ref=J1 }}\n*{{cite book |last=MacDonald |first=IG |year=2013 |title=Clerics and Clansmen: The Diocese of Argyll between the Twelfth and Sixteenth Centuries |series=The Northern World: North Europe and the Baltic c. 400\u20131700 AD. Peoples, Economics and Cultures (series vol. 61) |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]] |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-18547-0 |issn=1569-1462 |ref=M2 }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.theheraldrysociety.com/articles/scotland/ASA.htm |title=Some Ancient Scottish Arms |last=McAndrew |first=BA |year=1992 |website=[[The Heraldry Society]] |access-date=5 February 2014 |ref=M6 }}\n*{{cite journal |last=McAndrew |first=BA |year=1999 |title=The Sigillography of the Ragman Roll |url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/catalogue/adsdata/arch-352-1/dissemination/pdf/vol_129/129_663_752.pdf |journal=[[Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]] |volume= 129 |pages=663\u2013752 |ref=M4 }}\n*{{cite book |last=McAndrew |first=BA |year=2006 |title=Scotland's Historic Heraldry |publisher=[[Boydell Press]] |location=Woodbridge |isbn=9781843832614 |ref=M1 }}\n*{{cite book |last=McLeod |first=W |year=2005 |origyear=2004 |chapter=Political and Cultural Background |title=Divided Gaels: Gaelic Cultural Identities in Scotland and Ireland 1200\u20131650 |pages=14\u201354 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19-924722-6 |doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199247226.003.0002 |via=Oxford Scholarship Online |ref=M10 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Munro |first=J |year=1981 |chapter=The Lordship of the Isles |editor-last=Maclean |editor-first=L |title=The Middle Ages in the Highlands |publisher=Inverness Field Club |location=Inverness |ref=M9 }}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Munro |editor-first=RW |title=Munro's Western Isles of Scotland and Genealogies of the Clans, 1549 |year=1993 |origyear=1961 |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company |isbn=0-8063-5076-8 |ref=M8 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Oram |first=RD |authorlink=Richard Oram |year=2004 |chapter=The Lordship of the Isles, 1336\u20131545 |editor1-last=Omand |editor1-first=D |title=The Argyll Book |publisher=[[Birlinn Limited|Birlinn]] |location=Edinburgh |pages=123\u2013139 |isbn=1-84158-253-0 |ref=O2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Penman |first=MA |year=2005 |origyear=2004 |title=David II, 1329\u201371 |publisher=John Donald |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-85976-603-6 |ref=P2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Penman |first=MA |chapter=The MacDonald Lordship and the Bruce Dynasty, c.1306\u2013c.1371 |year=2014 |editor-last=Oram |editor-first=RD |editor-link=Richard Oram |title=The Lordship of the Isles |series=The Northern World: North Europe and the Baltic c. 400\u20131700 AD. Peoples, Economics and Cultures (series vol. 68) |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]] |location=Leiden |doi=10.1163/9789004279469_004 |isbn=978-90-04-28035-9 |issn=1569-1462 |pages=62\u201387 |doi-broken-date=2020-04-04 |ref=P1 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Sellar |first=WDH |authorlink=David Sellar |year=2000 |chapter=Hebridean Sea Kings: The Successors of Somerled, 1164\u20131316 |editor1-last=Cowan |editor1-first=EJ |editor1-link=Edward J. Cowan |editor2-last=McDonald |editor2-first=RA |title=Alba: Celtic Scotland in the Middle Ages |publisher=Tuckwell Press |location=East Linton |pages=187\u2013218 |isbn=1-86232-151-5 |ref=S1 }}\n*{{cite journal |year=2003 |last=Sellar |first=WDH |authorlink=David Sellar |title=Review of J Higgitt, The Murthly Hours: Devotion, Literacy and Luxury in Paris, England and the Gaelic West |journal=[[The Scottish Historical Review]] |volume= 82 |issue= 214 |pages=296\u2013297 |doi=10.3366/shr.2003.82.2.296 |jstor=25529723 |ref=S2 }}\n*{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/54284 |title=MacDougall, John, Lord of Argyll (''d''. 1316) |last=Sellar |first=WDH |authorlink=David Sellar |year=2004 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/54284 |access-date=5 July 2011 |ref=S3 }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Turner |first=D |year=1998 |title=The Bishops of Argyll and the Castle of Achanduin, Lismore, AD 1180\u20131343 |url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/catalogue/adsdata/arch-352-1/dissemination/pdf/vol_128/128_645_652.pdf |volume= 128 |journal=[[Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]] |publisher=[[Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]] |pages=645\u2013652 |ref=T9 }}\n*{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/1206 |title=Balliol, Edward (''b''. in or after 1281, ''d''. 1364) |last=Webster |first=B |year=2004 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/1206 |access-date=28 April 2012 |ref=W1 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MacDougall, John Gallda}}\n[[Category:Clan MacDougall|John]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 Parliament of Scotland]]\n[[Category:People from Lorne, Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish clan chiefs]]\n[[Category:Scottish people of the Wars of Scottish Independence]]\n", "name_user": "Hqb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSecondary sources:fix broken/dead doi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gallda_MacDougall"}
{"title_page": "Mike Skinner (musician)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|English rapper}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Mike Skinner\n| image = Mike Skinner of The Streets live at Parklife, Sydney 2011 02.jpg\n| caption = Skinner performing at a concert in 2011\n| img_size =\n| background = solo_singer\n| alias =\n| birth_name = Michael Geoffrey Skinner\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1979|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Chipping Barnet]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| origin = [[Birmingham]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* synthesizer\n* keyboard\n* guitar\n}}\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative hip hop]]\n* [[electronica]]\n* [[UK garage]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* songwriter\n* musician\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Locked On Records|Locked On]]\n* [[679 Artists|679]]\n* [[Vice Records|Vice]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[The Streets]]\n* [[And That|The D.O.T.]]\n}}\n| website = {{url|mikeskinner-ltd.co.uk/}}\n}}\n'''Michael Geoffrey Skinner''' (born 27 November 1979)<ref name=littlebritain>{{Citation |last= Bainbridge |first=Luke |year=2006 |title=The voice of little Britain |publisher=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2006/apr/09/7days4.news | quote= But Skinner has never hidden the fact that he comes from the suburbs. He was born in Barnet, north London and moved to West Heath, Birmingham at the age of five. 'You think I'm ghetto? Stop dreaming,' he mocked on his debut album. |accessdate=9 August 2019 }}</ref> is an English rapper, songwriter, musician, and record producer. He is best known for the music project [[The Streets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Streets bio at Yahoo! Music |url=http://music.yahoo.com/ar-296908-bio--The-Streets |accessdate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070110074234/http://music.yahoo.com/ar-296908-bio--The-Streets |archivedate=10 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSkinner was born in [[Chipping Barnet|Barnet]], but grew up in [[West Heath, West Midlands|West Heath]], [[Birmingham]].<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> He started playing with keyboards at the age of five.<ref name=BBC1>{{cite news |title=Mike Skinner: Voice of The Streets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2262033.stm |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |work=BBC News website |date=13 January 2003<!-- 20:15 (GMT) -->|accessdate=30 September 2007 |quote=The Streets, who have been given four Brit Award nominations, is the one-man band better known as Birmingham musician Mike Skinner.}}</ref> When he was seven years old he began experiencing symptoms of [[epilepsy]], which worsened in his early teens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,11710,1200042,00.html|date=25 April 2004|title=Interview: The Streets|newspaper=Guardian|accessdate=14 September 2007 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Thompson}}</ref> He began writing [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and garage music in his home in West Heath and later built a [[Recording studio#Isolation booth|sound booth]] in his bedroom, using a cupboard and a mattress.<ref name=BBC1>{{cite news |title=Mike Skinner: Voice of The Streets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2262033.stm |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |work=BBC News website |date=13 January 2003<!-- 20:15 (GMT) -->|accessdate=30 September 2007 |quote=The Streets, who have been given four Brit Award nominations, is the one-man band better known as Birmingham musician Mike Skinner.}}</ref> He describes his background as \"[[Barratt Developments|Barratt]] class: suburban estates, not poor but not much money about, really boring\".<ref name=BBC1/> \n\nAt age 19, Skinner moved to [[Australia]] with his girlfriend; the relationship quickly ended, but Skinner stayed there for a year.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> Upon his return to England, Skinner moved to south London.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> He sent a demo tape of an early version of what would become the song \"[[Has It Come to This?]]\" to a record shop run by [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Nick Worthington.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> The song was released as a single in 2001, through [[Locked On Records]].<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/>\n\n==Music career==\n===The Streets (1994&ndash;2011, 2017&ndash;present)===\nIn the albums Skinner made with The Streets he focused on vocals, arranging, composing, mixing, keyboards, and synthesizers.\n{{main|The Streets|The Streets discography}}\n\n===The Beats Recordings===\nIn 2005, Skinner and Ted Mayhem launched the independent record label The Beats Recordings. A subsidiary of [[679 Recordings]], The Beats was home to British hip hop acts such as [[The Mitchell Brothers]], [[Example (rapper)|Example]] and [[Professor Green]]. In a 2008 interview with ''[[NME]]'', Skinner announced that the label had shut down.<ref name=\"TheBeatsOver\">{{cite web |title=The Streets\u2019 Mike Skinner speaks about record label death |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-streets-70-1342988 |website=NME |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 2012, Skinner stated in an interview that the label was starting up again, in order to release a new D.O.C. album.<ref name=\"livemag\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BoX_xw6qZ1Q#! |title=Mike Skinner Exclusive \u2013 [Live Meets...] |author= |date=12 March 2012 |work=LiveMagUK |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===The D.O.T. and Tonga Balloon Gang (2011&ndash;present)===\nAfter shelving The Streets, Skinner launched a new project, called The D.O.T, along with Rob Harvey of [[The Music (band)|The Music]]. Harvey performs on vocals, allowing Skinner to \"further develop his production approach\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Martin |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/the-streets-mike-skinner-starts-new-band-the-dot/57749/ |title=The Streets' Mike Skinner Starts New Band: The D.O.T &#124; Prefix |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=21 October 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2013}}</ref> Their first album, ''[[And That]]'', was released on 22 October 2012.<ref name=\"NME (and that announcement)\">{{cite journal|title=The Streets' Mike Skinner and The Music's Rob Harvey announce new album and tour \u2013 ticket details|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-streets/65794|accessdate=8 October 2012|journal=[[NME]]|date=28 August 2012}}</ref> Their second album titled ''Diary'' was released on 5 May 2013.\n\nIn 2013, Skinner remixed Norwich rapper Context's song \"Small Town Lad Sentiments\". The remix features on Context's second EP, ''Hindsight is the Purest Form of Romance'' (2014). In 2015, he remixed [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]]' breakthrough single \"Cheer Up London\" alongside [[Jammer (rapper)|Jammer]]. The remix featured on an extended play exclusive to [[HMV]], released alongside the group's debut album ''Are You Satisfied?''.\n\nSkinner teamed up with UK rap group [[Murkage cartel|Murkage]] to form a supergroup entitled Tonga Balloon Gang, and they released an eponymous three-track EP on 14 November 2015.<ref>http://rwdmag.com/tonga-balloon-gang-murkage-dave-mike-skinner-oscar-worldpeace-gaika-klepto-dj-smith-to-release-ep-and-here-is-lead-single-make-no-scene/</ref> The release features additional vocals from Jammer and [[Big Narstie]].<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/tonga-balloon-gang-single/id1051688330</ref> In 2016 Skinner released a number of tracks on Soundcloud under the name The Darker the Shadow, The Brighter the Light. In April 2017 he released the song \"Bad Decisions In The Night\" on digital platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.loudandquiet.com/listening-post/mike-skinner-rapping-solo-project-darker-shadow-brighter-light|title=Mike Skinner is rapping again with his solo project The Darker the Shadow, The Brighter the Light|last=Tanti|first=Omar|date=10 April 2017|work=Loud And Quiet|access-date=2017-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Influences===\nSkinner is influenced by musical genres including [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[UK garage]], [[reggae]], and [[Country music|country and western music]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Mike Skinner from The Streets By Martin Worster|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eIjOF_tUXYk|accessdate=11 October 2012|location=YouTube|format=Video Interview}}</ref> Some of the many hip hop artists that influenced him in the making of some of The Streets' albums are [[DJ Premier]] and [[Erick Sermon]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Musical style===\nSkinner is best known for his lyricism matched with his blurring of musical styles of [[UK garage]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[indie rock]], [[reggae]] and [[ska]]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer Dave Simpson particularly praised Skinner's \"dazzling wordplay.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Simpson|first=Dave|title=The Streets Review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/22/the-streets-live-review|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Acting and movie work==\n===The Inbetweeners===\nThe soundtrack album for the film ''[[The Inbetweeners Movie]]'' was released in 2011, featuring nine new compositions by Skinner.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===''Beat Stevie''===\nAn online channel currently presented by Mike and business partner [[Ted Mayhem]], [[Beat Stevie]], is an \"anything goes\" blog/music show also shown on [[Channel 4]] in their [[4Music]] late night strand.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} The episodes often include backstage footage and onstage hijinks. Events documented in the show have also been mentioned in the early songs of [[Example (rapper)|Example]] and [[Professor Green]]. The 'funeral' of Skinner's record label \"The Beats\" was shown on the channel, with the mixtapes of [[The Mitchell Brothers]], Example and Professor Green being burnt in a fire of absinthe.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Acting===\nSkinner had a cameo role in the fifth series of ''[[Doctor Who]]'' as a security guard, featuring in the episode \"[[The Time of Angels]]\".<ref name=\"nme._TheS\">{{Cite web\n| title = The Streets' Mike Skinner makes 'Doctor Who' cameo {{!}} NME\n| author = \n| work = NME\n| date = 25 April 2010\n| access-date = 21 January 2020\n| url = https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-streets-16-1302490\n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 interview, Skinner also revealed that he would be starring in a film, a thriller set in a hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12350700 |title=Mike Skinner not sad at Streets demise |publisher=BBC |date=2 July 2011 |accessdate=2 July 2011}}</ref> Adding that it won't be a \"blockbuster\" and that it will take around two years to complete.\n\nSkinner guest-starred as Blockhead in one episode of ''[[Major Lazer (TV series)|Major Lazer]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Promotional and campaign work==\nIn 2005, Skinner signed up to appear in a twelve-month ad campaign for Reebok's \"I Am What I Am\" campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title=Softpedia article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok |publisher=Softpedia |date=26 August 2005 |url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/The-Streets-Star-Mike-Skinner-the-New-Face-of-Reebok-6971.shtml |accessdate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824141237/http://news.softpedia.com/news/The-Streets-Star-Mike-Skinner-the-New-Face-of-Reebok-6971.shtml |archivedate=24 August 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Farey-Jones | first = Daniel | title = Brand Republic article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok | publisher = Brand Republic | date = 25 August 2005|url = http://www.brandrepublic.com/login/News/492425/ | accessdate = 18 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/492425/mike-skinner-fronts-uk-only-i-am-i-am-campaign-reebok? | accessdate = 28 August 2016 | title = Mike Skinner fronts UK-only 'I Am What I Am' campaign for Reebok | publisher = [[Haymarket Media Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Evening Standard article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok | publisher = This Is London | date = 25 August 2005 | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-20175989-details/Streets+star+is+new+face+of+Reebokarticle.do;jsessionid=PW1wGfTQ18h54R1b0DSnm7vYFptpLyLNT613fLQw8h21R2L7DbHn!-1763085256!-1407319224!7001!-1 | accessdate = 18 July 2007}} {{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSkinner has always identified himself with Birmingham and he is a keen supporter of [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} He has worn the club's replica shirt on stage. He also wore it in the music video for his remix of [[Bloc Party]]'s single \"[[Banquet (song)|Banquet]]\".{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2008, Skinner took time off from The Streets to battle symptoms of [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] and later wrote the song \"Trying to Kill M.E.\" to document his fight against the disorder. In addition, he has tried to raise awareness that \"it's not just depression. That's what people tend to think\". Another statement he has released on the topic: \"I was incapacitated. It seems to have faded now. But at the time I think I was working too hard. It was important to just mention it really. It was such a big thing for me. It lasted about a year at its worst. I had to stop working.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Skinner Hopes to Raise Awareness of Fatigue Syndrome|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/229893/Skinner-hopes-to-raise-awareness-of-fatigue-syndrome|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Skinner married Claire Le Marquand in [[Antibes]] after the birth of their daughter Amelia in 2009. Skinner attributes the turnaround of his lifestyle, in regards to his dabbling with drugs, to the birth of his daughter and the responsibility of being a father.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Skinner Laid Bare in The Story of the Streets Autobiography |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/what-is-on-in-birmingham/rock-and-pop/2012/04/06/mike-skinner-laid-bare-in-the-story-of-the-streets-autobiography-97319-30705134/2/ |accessdate=11 October 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===The Streets===\n{{see also|The Streets discography}}\n*''[[Original Pirate Material]]'' (2002)\n*''[[A Grand Don't Come for Free]]'' (2004)\n*''[[The Hardest Way to Make an Easy Living]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Everything Is Borrowed]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Computers and Blues]]'' (2011)\n\n===The D.O.T===\n* ''[[And That]]'' (2012)\n* ''Diary'' (2013)\n\n===The Darker the Shadow The Brighter the Light===\n* ''Soundcloud Release'' (2017)\n\n==Biography==\n*''The Story of The Streets.'' London: [[Bantam Press]], 2012. By Mike Skinner. 304 pages. {{ISBN|978-0593068076}}. Biography recording his beginnings as a musician in the Birmingham suburbs in the garage scene, to his struggles as a commercial musician.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Skinner's The Story of The Streets|url=http://www.electronicbeats.net/2012/03/26/mike-skinners-the-story-of-the-streets/|accessdate=11 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001013355/http://www.electronicbeats.net/2012/03/26/mike-skinners-the-story-of-the-streets/|archive-date=1 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Streets}}\n* {{official website|www.the-streets.co.uk}}\n\n{{The Streets}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skinner, Mike}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:UK garage musicians]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Chipping Barnet]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|English rapper}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Mike Skinner\n| image = Mike Skinner of The Streets live at Parklife, Sydney 2011 02.jpg\n| caption = Skinner performing at a concert in 2011\n| img_size =\n| background = solo_singer\n| alias =\n| birth_name = Michael Geoffrey Skinner\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1979|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Chipping Barnet]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| origin = [[Birmingham]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* synthesizer\n* keyboard\n* guitar\n}}\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative hip hop]]\n* [[electronica]]\n* [[UK garage]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* songwriter\n* musician\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Locked On Records|Locked On]]\n* [[679 Artists|679]]\n* [[Vice Records|Vice]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[The Streets]]\n* [[And That|The D.O.T.]]\n}}\n| website = {{url|mikeskinner-ltd.co.uk/}}\n}}\n'''Michael Geoffrey Skinner''' (born 27 November 1979)<ref name=littlebritain>{{Citation |last= Bainbridge |first=Luke |year=2006 |title=The voice of little Britain |publisher=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2006/apr/09/7days4.news | quote= But Skinner has never hidden the fact that he comes from the suburbs. He was born in Barnet, north London and moved to West Heath, Birmingham at the age of five. 'You think I'm ghetto? Stop dreaming,' he mocked on his debut album. |accessdate=9 August 2019 }}</ref> is an English rapper, songwriter, musician, and record producer. He is best known for the music project [[The Streets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Streets bio at Yahoo! Music |url=http://music.yahoo.com/ar-296908-bio--The-Streets |accessdate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070110074234/http://music.yahoo.com/ar-296908-bio--The-Streets |archivedate=10 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSkinner was born in [[Chipping Barnet|Barnet]], but grew up in [[West Heath, West Midlands|West Heath]], [[Birmingham]].<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> He started playing with keyboards at the age of five.<ref name=BBC1>{{cite news |title=Mike Skinner: Voice of The Streets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2262033.stm |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |work=BBC News website |date=13 January 2003<!-- 20:15 (GMT) -->|accessdate=30 September 2007 |quote=The Streets, who have been given four Brit Award nominations, is the one-man band better known as Birmingham musician Mike Skinner.}}</ref> When he was seven years old he began experiencing symptoms of [[epilepsy]], which worsened in his early teens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,11710,1200042,00.html|date=25 April 2004|title=Interview: The Streets|newspaper=Guardian|accessdate=14 September 2007 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Thompson}}</ref> He began writing [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and garage music in his home in West Heath and later built a [[Recording studio#Isolation booth|sound booth]] in his bedroom, using a cupboard and a mattress.<ref name=BBC1>{{cite news |title=Mike Skinner: Voice of The Streets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2262033.stm |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |work=BBC News website |date=13 January 2003<!-- 20:15 (GMT) -->|accessdate=30 September 2007 |quote=The Streets, who have been given four Brit Award nominations, is the one-man band better known as Birmingham musician Mike Skinner.}}</ref> He describes his background as \"[[Barratt Developments|Barratt]] class: suburban estates, not poor but not much money about, really boring\".<ref name=BBC1/> \n\nAt age 19, Skinner moved to [[Australia]] with his girlfriend; the relationship quickly ended, but Skinner stayed there for a year.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> Upon his return to England, Skinner moved to south London.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> He sent a demo tape of an early version of what would become the song \"[[Has It Come to This?]]\" to a record shop run by [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Nick Worthington.<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/> The song was released as a single in 2001, through [[Locked On Records]].<ref name=\"littlebritain\"/>\n\n==Music career==\n===The Streets (1994&ndash;2011, 2017&ndash;present)===\nIn the albums Skinner made with The Streets he focused on vocals, arranging, composing, mixing, keyboards, and synthesizers.\n{{main|The Streets|The Streets discography}}\n\n===The Beats Recordings===\nIn 2005, Skinner and Ted Mayhem launched the independent record label The Beats Recordings. A subsidiary of [[679 Recordings]], The Beats was home to British hip-hop acts such as [[The Mitchell Brothers]], [[Example (rapper)|Example]] and [[Professor Green]]. In a 2008 interview with ''[[NME]]'', Skinner announced that the label had shut down.<ref name=\"TheBeatsOver\">{{cite web |title=The Streets\u2019 Mike Skinner speaks about record label death |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-streets-70-1342988 |website=NME |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 2012, Skinner stated in an interview that the label was starting up again, in order to release a new D.O.C. album.<ref name=\"livemag\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BoX_xw6qZ1Q#! |title=Mike Skinner Exclusive \u2013 [Live Meets...] |author= |date=12 March 2012 |work=LiveMagUK |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===The D.O.T. and Tonga Balloon Gang (2011&ndash;present)===\nAfter shelving The Streets, Skinner launched a new project, called The D.O.T, along with Rob Harvey of [[The Music (band)|The Music]]. Harvey performs on vocals, allowing Skinner to \"further develop his production approach\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Martin |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/the-streets-mike-skinner-starts-new-band-the-dot/57749/ |title=The Streets' Mike Skinner Starts New Band: The D.O.T &#124; Prefix |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=21 October 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2013}}</ref> Their first album, ''[[And That]]'', was released on 22 October 2012.<ref name=\"NME (and that announcement)\">{{cite journal|title=The Streets' Mike Skinner and The Music's Rob Harvey announce new album and tour \u2013 ticket details|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-streets/65794|accessdate=8 October 2012|journal=[[NME]]|date=28 August 2012}}</ref> Their second album titled ''Diary'' was released on 5 May 2013.\n\nIn 2013, Skinner remixed Norwich rapper Context's song \"Small Town Lad Sentiments\". The remix features on Context's second EP, ''Hindsight is the Purest Form of Romance'' (2014). In 2015, he remixed [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]]' breakthrough single \"Cheer Up London\" alongside [[Jammer (rapper)|Jammer]]. The remix featured on an extended play exclusive to [[HMV]], released alongside the group's debut album ''Are You Satisfied?''.\n\nSkinner teamed up with UK rap group [[Murkage cartel|Murkage]] to form a supergroup entitled Tonga Balloon Gang, and they released an eponymous three-track EP on 14 November 2015.<ref>http://rwdmag.com/tonga-balloon-gang-murkage-dave-mike-skinner-oscar-worldpeace-gaika-klepto-dj-smith-to-release-ep-and-here-is-lead-single-make-no-scene/</ref> The release features additional vocals from Jammer and [[Big Narstie]].<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/tonga-balloon-gang-single/id1051688330</ref> In 2016 Skinner released a number of tracks on Soundcloud under the name The Darker the Shadow, The Brighter the Light. In April 2017 he released the song \"Bad Decisions In The Night\" on digital platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.loudandquiet.com/listening-post/mike-skinner-rapping-solo-project-darker-shadow-brighter-light|title=Mike Skinner is rapping again with his solo project The Darker the Shadow, The Brighter the Light|last=Tanti|first=Omar|date=10 April 2017|work=Loud And Quiet|access-date=2017-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Influences===\nSkinner is influenced by musical genres including [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[UK garage]], [[reggae]], and [[Country music|country and western music]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Mike Skinner from The Streets By Martin Worster|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eIjOF_tUXYk|accessdate=11 October 2012|location=YouTube|format=Video Interview}}</ref> Some of the many hip hop artists that influenced him in the making of some of The Streets' albums are [[DJ Premier]] and [[Erick Sermon]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Musical style===\nSkinner is best known for his lyricism matched with his blurring of musical styles of [[UK garage]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[indie rock]], [[reggae]] and [[ska]]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer Dave Simpson particularly praised Skinner's \"dazzling wordplay.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Simpson|first=Dave|title=The Streets Review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/22/the-streets-live-review|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Acting and movie work==\n===The Inbetweeners===\nThe soundtrack album for the film ''[[The Inbetweeners Movie]]'' was released in 2011, featuring nine new compositions by Skinner.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===''Beat Stevie''===\nAn online channel currently presented by Mike and business partner [[Ted Mayhem]], [[Beat Stevie]], is an \"anything goes\" blog/music show also shown on [[Channel 4]] in their [[4Music]] late night strand.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} The episodes often include backstage footage and onstage hijinks. Events documented in the show have also been mentioned in the early songs of [[Example (rapper)|Example]] and [[Professor Green]]. The 'funeral' of Skinner's record label \"The Beats\" was shown on the channel, with the mixtapes of [[The Mitchell Brothers]], Example and Professor Green being burnt in a fire of absinthe.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Acting===\nSkinner had a cameo role in the fifth series of ''[[Doctor Who]]'' as a security guard, featuring in the episode \"[[The Time of Angels]]\".<ref name=\"nme._TheS\">{{Cite web\n| title = The Streets' Mike Skinner makes 'Doctor Who' cameo {{!}} NME\n| author = \n| work = NME\n| date = 25 April 2010\n| access-date = 21 January 2020\n| url = https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-streets-16-1302490\n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 interview, Skinner also revealed that he would be starring in a film, a thriller set in a hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12350700 |title=Mike Skinner not sad at Streets demise |publisher=BBC |date=2 July 2011 |accessdate=2 July 2011}}</ref> Adding that it won't be a \"blockbuster\" and that it will take around two years to complete.\n\nSkinner guest-starred as Blockhead in one episode of ''[[Major Lazer (TV series)|Major Lazer]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Promotional and campaign work==\nIn 2005, Skinner signed up to appear in a twelve-month ad campaign for Reebok's \"I Am What I Am\" campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title=Softpedia article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok |publisher=Softpedia |date=26 August 2005 |url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/The-Streets-Star-Mike-Skinner-the-New-Face-of-Reebok-6971.shtml |accessdate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824141237/http://news.softpedia.com/news/The-Streets-Star-Mike-Skinner-the-New-Face-of-Reebok-6971.shtml |archivedate=24 August 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Farey-Jones | first = Daniel | title = Brand Republic article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok | publisher = Brand Republic | date = 25 August 2005|url = http://www.brandrepublic.com/login/News/492425/ | accessdate = 18 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/492425/mike-skinner-fronts-uk-only-i-am-i-am-campaign-reebok? | accessdate = 28 August 2016 | title = Mike Skinner fronts UK-only 'I Am What I Am' campaign for Reebok | publisher = [[Haymarket Media Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Evening Standard article detailing relationship between Skinner and Reebok | publisher = This Is London | date = 25 August 2005 | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-20175989-details/Streets+star+is+new+face+of+Reebokarticle.do;jsessionid=PW1wGfTQ18h54R1b0DSnm7vYFptpLyLNT613fLQw8h21R2L7DbHn!-1763085256!-1407319224!7001!-1 | accessdate = 18 July 2007}} {{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSkinner has always identified himself with Birmingham and he is a keen supporter of [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} He has worn the club's replica shirt on stage. He also wore it in the music video for his remix of [[Bloc Party]]'s single \"[[Banquet (song)|Banquet]]\".{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2008, Skinner took time off from The Streets to battle symptoms of [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] and later wrote the song \"Trying to Kill M.E.\" to document his fight against the disorder. In addition, he has tried to raise awareness that \"it's not just depression. That's what people tend to think\". Another statement he has released on the topic: \"I was incapacitated. It seems to have faded now. But at the time I think I was working too hard. It was important to just mention it really. It was such a big thing for me. It lasted about a year at its worst. I had to stop working.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Skinner Hopes to Raise Awareness of Fatigue Syndrome|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/229893/Skinner-hopes-to-raise-awareness-of-fatigue-syndrome|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Skinner married Claire Le Marquand in [[Antibes]] after the birth of their daughter Amelia in 2009. Skinner attributes the turnaround of his lifestyle, in regards to his dabbling with drugs, to the birth of his daughter and the responsibility of being a father.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Skinner Laid Bare in The Story of the Streets Autobiography |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/what-is-on-in-birmingham/rock-and-pop/2012/04/06/mike-skinner-laid-bare-in-the-story-of-the-streets-autobiography-97319-30705134/2/ |accessdate=11 October 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===The Streets===\n{{see also|The Streets discography}}\n*''[[Original Pirate Material]]'' (2002)\n*''[[A Grand Don't Come for Free]]'' (2004)\n*''[[The Hardest Way to Make an Easy Living]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Everything Is Borrowed]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Computers and Blues]]'' (2011)\n\n===The D.O.T===\n* ''[[And That]]'' (2012)\n* ''Diary'' (2013)\n\n===The Darker the Shadow The Brighter the Light===\n* ''Soundcloud Release'' (2017)\n\n==Biography==\n*''The Story of The Streets.'' London: [[Bantam Press]], 2012. By Mike Skinner. 304 pages. {{ISBN|978-0593068076}}. Biography recording his beginnings as a musician in the Birmingham suburbs in the garage scene, to his struggles as a commercial musician.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Skinner's The Story of The Streets|url=http://www.electronicbeats.net/2012/03/26/mike-skinners-the-story-of-the-streets/|accessdate=11 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001013355/http://www.electronicbeats.net/2012/03/26/mike-skinners-the-story-of-the-streets/|archive-date=1 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Streets}}\n* {{official website|www.the-streets.co.uk}}\n\n{{The Streets}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skinner, Mike}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:UK garage musicians]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Chipping Barnet]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Aitch & Aitch Aitch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Beats Recordings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Skinner_(musician)"}
